body:
@arniu, I see what you mean about `abstract-logging` can you provide an example of the issues this causes? 

I tested using TS and don't see any issue or error. `abstract-logging` [is a noop](https://github.com/jsumners/abstract-logging/blob/master/index.js), so it has no effect if you call it regardless of args. Tested it like so:

```ts
import * as fastify from 'fastify'

const server = fastify()

// Declare a route
server.get('/', (request, reply) => {
    server.log.warn('uh oh')
    reply.send({ hello: 'world' })
})

// Run the server!
server.listen(3000, (err, address) => {
    if (err) throw err
    server.log.info(`server listening on ${address}`)
})
```

`abstract-logging` only has `fatal`, `error`, `warn`, `info`, `debug` and `trace`, which is only a subset of `pino.Logger`'s. According to the type definition, users may use exclusive methods:

```
server.register((instance, opts, next) => {
    // `pino.Logger` is an instance of `EventEmitter`.
    // Calling `addListener` on `abstract-logging` will break the code.
    server.log.addListener('level-change', console.log)
})
```

@arniu I see what you mean now. This is actually a bigger issue beyond TypeScript.

@fastify/fastify, what are your thoughts on this? If logging is not enabled then `server.log` has a different set of methods. Should this be addressed?

If not we can potentially update the `fastify.d.ts` to provide correct typings if `options.logger` is "falsey"?
